    quizTitle: "DE genes I checkpoint quiz", writtenTitle: "Written exam trainer", writtenPrompt: "Write a 10–12-line answer: how do you choose the correct statistical test for one gene measured in two groups?", writtenPlaceholder: "Start from the biological question and experimental design...", writtenModel: "For one gene measured in two groups, I first define the biological question and whether the two groups are dependent or independent. Before/after data from the same subject are paired; case-control or two different diseases are unpaired. Then I inspect the distribution and, if needed, apply Shapiro–Wilk to check normality. If paired and normal, I use paired Student t-test; if paired but non-normal or with outliers, Wilcoxon signed-rank. If unpaired and normal with similar variance, I use unpaired t-test; if variances or sample sizes differ, Welch correction. If unpaired and non-parametric, I use Mann–Whitney/Wilcoxon rank-sum. Finally I compare p with alpha and interpret the biological direction and confidence.",
